<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Wherefore, putting away lying</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Of this sin the heathen were very guilty, affirming that a profitable lie was better than a hurtful truth.  That branch of the new man that must be put on in opposition to it is speaking the truth in all our converse with others.  All who have grace make conscience of speaking the truth.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>We are members one of another</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
Truth is a debt we owe to one another; and, if we love one another, we shall not deceive one another.  We belong to the same society or body, which falsehood or lying tends to dissolve; and therefore we should avoid it, and speak truth.<br>
<br>
vs.26)<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Be you angry, and sin not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  This we are apt enough to be, God knows:  but we find it difficult enough to observe the restriction, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>and sin not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  ...One great and common sin in anger is to suffer it to burn into wrath, and then to let it rest.  Before night calm and quiet your spirits, be reconciled to the offender: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Let not the sun go down upon your wrath</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Though anger in itself is not sinful, yet there is the utmost danger of its becoming so if it be not carefully watched.  <br>
<br>
vs. 27) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Neither give place to the devil</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Those who persevere in sinful anger and in wrath let the devil into their hearts. Let your ears be deaf to whisperers, tale-bearers, and slanderers.  We are here warned against the sin of stealing, and advised to honest industry and to beneficence: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Let him that stole steal no more, </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
vs. 28) But we must not only take heed of the sin, but conscientiously abound in the opposite duty;  not only not steal, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>but rather let him labour, working with his hands the thing that is good.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Idleness makes theives.  Men should therefore be diligent and industrious, not in any unlawful way, but in some honest calling:  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Working the thing which is good</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Industry will keep people out of temptation of doing wrong.  They must labor not only that they may live themselves, ...those who have but little for themselves, must cast their mite into the treasury.  God must have his dues and the poor are his receivers.&quot;<br>
